36:10 Janelle's dress is based on Picasso, of course! If anything artistic could be described as "camp", it would be Picasso all the way.   If you're interested in a tiny background of him, his entire life was essentially an ode to camp culture. Today, we know him best for his strange, 3D-but-2D style of abstract art. However, he was so much more at the time. He mastered everything from abstract sculpting to realist painting, but he worked in phases. Picasso would obsessively work in one art style until he was known worldwide for his accomplishments in that field...and then he'd take a sharp turn into something drastically different, and start the process all over again. Whenever he would get pinned down with one style, he immediately felt the need to express something new. What better way is there to exude "camp" than that?

from my understanding, frank, and kanye too, hit the mark on the camp theme by being as minimal as possible. one of the things which i think many failed to consider this year is the line from Sontag's essay where she describes camp as a "private code". the night saw stars tryna out-do eachother in bigger and bolder looks and in it they failed to hit upon what frank did- the idea of staying true to yourself and being extraordinary, even in an ordinary way. plus, people's reactions to his sullen expressions and "basic" fit say it all; they're outraged by his apparent disinterest and lack of effort but in that outrage is the true meaning of camp. the ironic value of such a minimal look at what should be the most extravagant met gala is truly wonderful, and more importantly for the theme, true to frank and wholly unexpected
i don't study fashion though, and i'm sorry to say i've only read a summary of "notes on camp", but this is how the fit translated to me at least

love my drag sisters but the term "Camp" wasn't even coined by queens. It was a term used to describe low budget tackily dressed 1960's colour films, such as teen beach movies or basically anything with Elvis in it. All it did was prove to me that almost no one today understands what camp is.    Of course Sontag did not invent it and neither did black drag queens (enuf with the credit appropriations, which is SO neo-Soviet.), although Sontag helped explain it and black drag queens, black fancy men, other black entertainers and many other African Americans certainly were co-developers. And Sontag did more damage than good, rather like a Southern Baptist in 1928 trying to codify Harlem jazz to her fellow congregants after a trip the NYC.   Camp can be self-conscious about itself or clueless about itself, but it requires an insider/outsider dynamic. Camp is an exchange. It is not mere exaggeration or ugliness. It is not just "over the top" or hideous or wrong. It is not about misused media or inappropriate fabrics. Subversion and transgression are involved, but only with commitment.    If it is self-conscious, it needs the friction between the people who get it and the people who don't. HauteLeMode's spokesspeaker is right about the performance aspect of camp. And, too, if it is NOT self-aware, it requires others to see its campiness and celebrate it. Edith Massey in her debutante dress in "Polyester" may well have felt pretty. Her unselfconsciousness delivered, however, because she was used as to deliver a camp expression (again) by Waters and the audience got it.     Camp, in its delivery, also needs a point. Camp does not exist unless it has a purpose. What we saw here was people for whom the purpose almost always was to LOOK CAMPY. That is as far from the point as it could get.    So for the Met Gala, we had a pack of clueless celebrities in the hands of non-savvy designers attempting to exhibit a concept they didn't understand and certainly cannot embody. Apart from a couple pieces, camp was not presented and it certainly was not celebrated except as a target to try to hit. In this setting it probably could not be achieved. All we could get was a costume parade of people vying for "most silly." The people mostly lacked commitment, either to cluelessly deliver something they thought was fabulous for our informed enjoyment in quite a different way, or to say something in an outrageously driven way that expressed an emotion, a position or a cultural statement with absurdity, wit and true fabulousness in mind and heart.   Any event where Kim Kardashian being herself was one of the highlights (ugh) shows the errors involved.    But the signal camp moment was Cher performing, which by itself lifted the whole thing out of the pit of confused and monied ego and flung a good measure of perfumed horse shit back into the faces of the zombies in attendance. To put it campily: brava.
